The s-s-h agent and agent forwarding.

A passphrase-protected key is more secure, but on its own it is inconvenient, because you would have to type the passphrase on every single connection. The s-s-h agent solves this. It is a small program that holds your decrypted keys in memory, so you enter the passphrase just once per session and the agent answers the server's challenges from then on.

On most desktop systems the agent starts automatically when you log in. You can check what it is holding by listing its keys with s-s-h-add dash l. To load a key into it you run s-s-h-add, which adds your default key, or name a specific key file. You can remove all keys with dash capital-d, or add a key with a time limit so it is forgotten after, say, an hour. If the agent is not running, you can start it and add your key by hand.

The agent also enables a powerful feature called agent forwarding, which matters when you s-s-h into one server and from there need to s-s-h onward to another. You have three options. You could copy your private key onto the first server, but that is bad, because it puts your key somewhere it could be stolen. You could generate a separate key on that intermediate machine, which works but means more keys to manage. Or you can use agent forwarding, which lets the s-s-h process on the first server reach back and ask your local agent to sign the challenge for the next hop. The key itself never leaves your machine. You enable it with the dash capital-a flag or a forward-agent setting in your config. But there is a real security caveat: while you are connected, the intermediate host can use your agent, so never enable it for servers you do not trust. In most cases proxy-jump is the safer choice, since it tunnels through the bastion without ever giving it access to your agent.
